\f2\emdash\f1  JERRY TRAUNFELD, THE HERBFARM (WOODINVILLE, WASHINGTON)\par
If you stay in the boundaries of what people think a dessert should be it gets very\par
hard to do something new. We explain that they already eat carrot cake. We think\par
parsnip will work instead of carrot and that kabocha squash will work instead of\par
pumpkin in a pie.\par
When people see eggplant in a dessert they automatically think it will not\par
work. You have to hide the unusual element and play up what people know\par
already. The boundaries are limitless when you think of all the crossovers\par
between sweet and savory. Duck \'e0 l\rquote orange is a fruit and meat combined, so why\par
not use bacon in a dessert? A pancake with maple syrup and bacon on the plate is\par
really sweet and savory. So people already eat these combinations\par
unconsciously.\par
For our apple-eggplant dessert, we start with a choux dough piecrust. Then we\par
layer an almond cream-like custard. Then we alternate apple and eggplant slices\par
side by side. We use baby eggplant because it has a spongy texture and sucks up\par
moisture from the cream that can otherwise make the crust soggy and absorb the\par
juice and flavor from the apples that would normally just evaporate. So when\par
you eat the eggplant and apples, the eggplant tastes like apples.\par
