Daniel Humm of New York\rquote s Eleven Madison Park on Making\par
Asparagus Soup\par
Making and seasoning soup is one of the best ways to learn about flavor. Let\rquote s\par
make asparagus soup:\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need a lot of asparagus flavor.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need acidity.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need sweetness that will come from the asparagus.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need the right amount of salt.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need just the right amount of spice, so that it doesn\rquote t actually taste\par
spicy. We use a lot of cayenne, but you would never know it is there; it is\par
just an accent.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You need fresh lime juice to finish.\par
Soup is a play of balance when you have a lot of flavor. You can add a lot of salt\par
and it won\rquote t taste salty. You can add a lot of acid and it won\rquote t taste acidic. But\par
you still have a bold-flavored soup. It\rquote s like winemaking; at some point, there is\par
a balance of all the flavors.\par
The first thing you need to do is get all the asparagus flavor into the soup at\par
the start. We save our asparagus liquid from all the asparagus we cook to use for\par
asparagus stock.\par
Making the soup: We sweat the asparagus [that is, cook it over low heat in a\par
little fat, generally in a covered pot or pan] very slowly. When we add wine, we\par
do it multiple times, adding a little at a time and reducing it, then repeating the\par
process. What this does is concentrate the flavor at each step. It makes a big\par
difference [before adding the asparagus liquid].\par
Finishing the soup: A soup may taste seasoned, but it still needs to be \ldblquote woken\par
up.\rdblquote  You taste the asparagus, but maybe it doesn\rquote t blow you away at first. To do\par
that, you need acid and cayenne. We season the soup with lime because it is a\par
stronger acid and yet has less flavor than lemon. If I use lemon to get as much\par
acid as I need for the soup, I will need to use so much that the soup will taste\par
lemony instead.\par
