Fava beans have a great flavor. Cooks in the past would blanch them, and the\par
flavor would be left in the water. Today, what I like to do with favas and other\par
vegetables is to put them in a pan with a little water, olive oil, or butter, and to\par
cover them while they cook. That way, all the flavor stays in the vegetables. If I\par
could cook for my customers the way I like to cook and eat at home, I would\par
sweat some spring onions in a pan with butter or oil, covered, to keep in the\par
flavor. Then I\rquote d add the shucked fava beans and let them cook with a little water.\par
At the last second, I\rquote d toss in some chopped parsley or basil, and there\rquote s your\par
sauce. This would be great under some fish. If you added some thyme and\par
maybe a little lamb jus, it would also work with lamb.\par
