Michael Lomonaco of Porter House New York on Cooking Steak\par
Aging: Aging is important because it tenderizes the steak. The aging process\par
breaks down the fibers and dehydrates the steak, concentrating its flavor. A dryaged steak has a more minerally and sharp edge to it, versus fresh meat that\par
tastes sweeter. It is critical to the flavor and adds to the cost because it takes four\par
weeks of aging to achieve it.\par
Seasoning: All our steaks are seasoned with coarse kosher salt and freshly\par
ground black pepper just prior to cooking, which draws out the flavor while they\par
cook. A squeeze of lemon makes a good Tuscan steak taste even better. If you\par
are in Italy and eating \ldblquote bistecca Fiorentina,\rdblquote  what you are having is an Italian\par
porterhouse. The steak is grilled over dried grape vines and served with a drizzle\par
of green olive oil from the first pressing of the new harvest and lemons on the\par
side.\par
Cooking: A steak should be cooked rare to medium rare. \ldblquote Rare\rdblquote  is a little\par
cool inside and hot on the exterior. \ldblquote Medium rare\rdblquote  is just a shade past, and only\par
warm in the middle. Cooking a steak beyond that point, it starts to toughen up\par
and the fat oozes out, making it increasingly dry and tough.\par
Saucing: Part of looking forward is looking back. Sauces provide the\par
connection to historical French and Italian cooking. In the gastronomic world,\par
the saucier was the top cook in the kitchen. It is all about building layer upon\par
layer of complexity in a sauce. It is most often sweet and sour, to cut through the\par
richness of the fat of the steak. Red wine sauce has the acidity to cut richness,\par
with sweetness from caramelized shallots, and it enhances the beef flavor. We\par
also make a homemade barbecue sauce as our steak sauce, which is sweet from\par
light brown sugar and molasses, tart from red wine vinegar, and smoky from\par
chipotle peppers.\par
Hanger steak is known as an onglet in French and is found on bistro menus. It is\par
also a great value, which is why you see it on menus in smaller restaurants. A\par
hanger steak is incredibly flavorful. There is only one per carcass, and it comes\par
from the area close to the kidneys, so it has almost an offal flavor to the beef. It\par
has become popular because it is different and not a typical-tasting steak. I like a\par
hanger steak grilled and served rare to medium rare. Slicing is also important,\par
because you have to cut it on the bias so that it is tender. I like a hanger steak\par
served with a traditional sauce, such as a caramelized shallot and red wine sauce\par
or a bourbon peppercorn sauce. It is important to caramelize the shallots so they\par
get sweet and offset the gaminess of the steak. I use bourbon instead of cognac\par
because it has more punch to it, and I\rquote ll use four different peppercorns \f2\emdash\f1  white,\par
black, pink, and green \f2\emdash\f1  with the last two modulating the flavor. Green\par
peppercorns have the sharpness to cut through the richness.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  MICHAEL LOMONACO, PORTER HOUSE NEW YORK (NEW YORK CITY)\par
Rib steak is the most popular cut next to filet mignon. The cut comes from the\par
rib roast, where one end meets the chuck at the fattier end and the other meets\par
the short loin at the leaner end. The rib steak that meets the chuck end is the\par
most popular and can even have a big knot of fat in it. This is one of my favorite\par
steaks. A big, fatty, juicy rib steak can\rquote t be beat on the grill. I cook these bone-on\par
because it gives more beef flavor. We do a Brandt Ranch cut that comes from\par
California just north of Mexico. That area has lots of flavor influences, so I\par
choose to do a chili rub on the steak. The cut is Holstein, which has a sweeter\par
edge to its meat. We grill it so that fat melts away and bastes it as it cooks. At the\par
end, we brush it with a blend of ancho chili, light brown sugar, toasted ground\par
cumin seeds, chipotle chile, and a pinch of cayenne. Then we char it one more\par
time, so that is like reseasoning the meat.\par
