Customers are picky at brunch. They have all cooked what they think they like,\par
they think they can do it slightly better than we can, and they want it twice as\par
fast. So, we take the classics like pancakes or French toast, use them as building\par
blocks, and push them a little further.\par
We will offer seasonal pancakes. In the winter, we\rquote ll make buckwheat\par
pancakes with cinnamon and glazed oranges. Bridging spring into summer, we\rquote ll\par
offer corn and saffron pancakes with a spicy poached pear and fresh ricotta.\par
Saffron and corn work really well together because of the floral nature of the\par
saffron and sweetness of the corn. We will use poached pears on the pancakes\par
until switching to blueberries for the summer, which give a real pop. The pears\par
are poached in a red wine syrup with aleppo chile that is a sun-dried chile with a\par
rich, round, sweet spice to it. The chile is not noticeable, but it acts like an acid\par
by lightening, plus cutting the sugar and richness of, the pancake.\par
When people eat pancakes, they naturally reach for butter. I don\rquote t serve butter\par
with my pancakes and instead serve fresh ricotta. We use ricotta from Anne\par
