in a pan so that the edges just get brown because that tastes really good. We\par
figured that out by mistake by putting cabbage into too hot a pan. After the chef\par
raised his voice about how that is the wrong way to cook cabbage, we tasted it,\par
and it was good! We now serve a green cabbage dish cooked this way with\par
caraway seeds and walnuts, then deglazed with Calvados. We also add a little\par
cider vinegar and olive oil to finish. It is a nice, easy marriage. It is not an\par
unpredictable marriage; these things just all work together. We pair this with\par
braised pork belly, but it would also work with a roasted breast of squab with its\par
leg done in a confit.\par
