Thumbelina carrots are something I missed when I moved from working in the\par
country [i.e., Pocantico Hills, New York, where Blue Hill at Stone Barns is\par
located] into Manhattan. Luckily, I recently found these short, fat carrots at the\par
green market. We saut\'e9 these carrots over an open fire so that they get a little\par
smoky. When they are cooked, they become soft and creamy. Once cooked, we\par
turn them into a puree with a shot of carrot juice at the last second. We pair this\par
with farro that has been cooked like risotto, then add some pine nuts and more\par
Thumbelina carrots that have been quartered. I don\rquote t know what is more\par
seductive: the smooth carrot farro with its light carrot flavor or the carrots\par
themselves that are totally creamy. The dish has no butter or cream but that is not\par
because we are trying to be healthy. The dish just doesn\rquote t need it.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  MICHAEL ANTHONY, GRAMERCY TAVERN (NEW YORK CITY)\par
Juices are a great way to freshen up a dish. If you cook a carrot, you lose the\par
\ldblquote carrotiness\rdblquote  of it. If you make a carrot soup with cooked carrots, it doesn\rquote t\par
become bright. So now we do a carrot base with cooked organic carrots with\par
tops, onions, garlic, and maybe some ginger and lemongrass. With that base we\par
make a really thick soup and then add carrot juice to it. In the end you have fresh\par
and cooked carrots for a better flavor profile.\par
