Since cheese is a near-perfect food, I sometimes look for the few nutrients\par
missing in cheese that can be found in other foods. The two essential nutrients\par
that cheese does not provide are vitamin C and fiber. This recommends fruits\par
especially \f2\emdash\f1  and makes a great start to the day: cheese, some high-fiber vitamin\par
C\f2\endash\f1 rich fruit, some whole grain organic bread, and coffee. The breads I prefer\par
with cheese are usually neutral flavored, though I fully appreciate the nutty or\par
herbed or fruity breads as natural partners for cheeses. The main reason I prefer\par
neutral flavors in my breads is because I don\rquote t want to meddle with the flavors in\par
the cheeses themselves. I\rquote m kind of a purist on that! Usually, the softer the\par
cheese, the harder the bread \f2\emdash\f1  to an extent. And high-pectin, high-fiber fruits\par
[e.g., apples, pears, apricots, plums, nectarines, peaches, figs] make natural\par
accompaniments for many, many cheeses.\par
Which cheeses? My faves with my espresso to which I add a little unfiltered raw\par
honey would be the pressed sheep milk cheeses: Ossau Iraty, Roncal, Zamorano,\par
Berkswell, Spenwood, Trade Lake Cedar, Vermont Shepherd, manchego, or\par
Pecorino Foglie Noce. But I\rquote m happy with whatever is looking good, and\par
preferably the harder aged cheeses: sheep, goat, or cow.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  MAX McCALMAN, ARTISANAL CHEESE CENTER (NEW YORK CITY)\par
With aged or strong cheese, you need something fruity or sweet to contrast with\par
the strong flavor. Pecorino is very strong, so you need something sweet with it.\par
With an aged or hard cheese, I like to serve some chestnut honey, a fruit jam, or\par
watermelon confiture. If I have some aged goat cheese, I like a mostarda [Italian\par
mustard fruit]. With sharper cheese, I also like a nice sweet wine, especially an\par
Italian Passito. With fresh young cheese, I simply like some good bread.\par
Chestnut honey, while good with aged cheese, does not work with a young\par
cheese.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  ODETTE FADA, SAN DOMENICO (NEW YORK CITY)\par
Honey, jam, and mostarda go great with cheese. Most honey works best with\par
younger cheeses and soft-ripened cheeses, especially if they have a chalky\par
quality to them. I love mountain Gorgonzola with chestnut honey; it is crazy! In\par
Italy, we call jam a confitura or marmalata. I like it with saltier cheeses like\par
Parmesan, or with more assertive cheeses. Mostarda is made of fruits cooked in\par
a white wine mustard syrup until they are candied. So, you have a sweet candy\par
effect with the spicy mustard. It goes with any savory firm cheese, and\par
particularly well with pecorino and Taleggio.\par
