Andrew Carmellini of New York\rquote s A Voce on Cooking Chicken as\par
a Two-Part Process \f2\emdash\f1  and Applying It to Chicken Cacciatore\par
1. Brining: Sometimes the older techniques inspire me for deeper flavors.\par
Many of these techniques are overlooked. Take brining, for instance. Brining has\par
been done forever with pork chops and chicken, and for the last five years you\par
have heard about it with turkey. The success of brining is more about the salt and\par
it getting in there and softening the protein strands. It is less about all the other\par
flavoring agents.\par
If you want to get started in your kitchen, start with a skin-and bone-on\par
chicken breast. Grab some kosher salt, sugar, or honey as I do, some water, and\par
brine the breast for 30 minutes. When you pull it out of the brine, rinse it, dry it,\par
and let it sit in the refrigerator for a couple of hours so the moisture comes out.\par
You will notice the difference in the texture. The marinated chicken \f2\emdash\f1  even if\par
you overcook it \f2\emdash\f1  will not be dry. It is the best.\par
2. Marinating: The chicken on my menu right now is brined and then\par
marinated for 24 hours. It is crazy how good the chicken becomes. The marinade\par
is made up of roasted garlic, Sicilian oregano, red pepper flakes, lots of lemon,\par
thyme, and olive oil. We joke that it tastes like Zesty Italian Wish-Bone\par
Dressing. It is so delicious.\par
The finished dish is served with poached and saut\'e9ed artichoke, roasted\par
pepper grilled over wood, fennel, and roasted spring onions. These vegetables\par
are all tossed with pesto, and the dish is finished with a tomato sauce made with\par
foamy tomato water and thyme.\par
Chicken Cacciatore\par
We opened up A Voce with chicken cacciatore on our menu and when people\par
heard the name of the dish, they\rquote d just yawn. A lot of times, this dish is just\par
chicken scaloppine with peppers and tomatoes. Ours is a whole different dish:\par
the chicken is on the bone, and brined first, which makes it nice and moist. With\par
it, we serve a homemade peperonata with roasted peppers, onions, garlic, red\par
pepper flakes, rosemary, fresh bay leaf, fresh thyme, and piment d\rquote Espelette [a\par
pepper from France with a smoky flavor]. Here is a place where technique plays\par
a role in the flavor: When you roast peppers, the best way to get the skin off is to\par
put them in a bowl covered with plastic wrap and let them steam. When they are\par
done, you are left with the pepper liquid. What we do is cook with that liquid.\par
To finish this dish, we put a big scoop of the pepper mixture, tomato sauce,\par
garlic puree, onion, red wine vinegar, and fresh bay leaf on the chicken and put it\par
in the oven to roast. The chicken cooks in its own juice then is served with\par
roasted potatoes. It is delicious.\par
What we are doing is layering the flavors. You have the technique of brining\par
the chicken, elevating the flavor profile of the peppers with the sweetness of the\par
onions and herbs, adding a little heat from the piment d\rquote Espelette, and giving\par
body to the sauce from the pepper juice, which is distilled pepper brandy.\par
