People always ask why I use bittersweet versus semisweet chocolate. Semisweet\par
is chocolate that needs salt. When you add salt to it, it brings up the bitter flavor\par
and makes it taste bittersweet. Semisweet chocolate to me tastes kind of flat.\par
Milk chocolate can taste flat as well. Now that there is Scharffen Berger and El\par
Rey on the market, I find both those chocolates to be really, really great, with\par
both flavor and kick to them. But if you want a killer chocolate dessert, don\rquote t use\par
milk chocolate.\par
When I write a dessert menu, there will be a couple of chocolate desserts, with\par
one being a killer chocolate and the other a lighter option, like chocolate with\par
bananas. If you don\rquote t have something intensely chocolate, chocolate lovers are\par
very, very unhappy. Banana souffl\'e9 with chocolate is not considered a chocolate\par
dessert. You have to be careful with a killer chocolate dessert \f2\emdash\f1  you can\rquote t just\par
put chocolate, chocolate, and chocolate together. There has to be balance so the\par
dessert is not too rich. To achieve balance, turn to coffee or caramel because they\par
pair so well and help to intensify the chocolate flavor.\par
For some desserts, I like to combine white and dark chocolate, or milk and\par
dark chocolate, to give balance and cut intensity. It sounds crazy, but you can use\par
one chocolate to mellow the flavor of another.\par
