My coconut rice pudding strudel was the result of Takashi\rquote s influence. [Takashi\par
Yagihashi was his chef at Detroit\rquote s Tribute restaurant.] Dessert has to make sense\par
in the context of the rest of the meal. Being a pastry chef is exciting because you\par
have a lot of autonomy, but you are still working within the chef\rquote s framework.\par
Takashi\rquote s food was very Asian-influenced. This dish was meant to bring in Asian\par
ingredients in a new way yet be something familiar.\par
So we have rice pudding flavored with coconut, lemongrass, ginger, and\par
vanilla, and diced apricot for texture. At the time I was introduced to frie de\par
brique, which is a Moroccan dough that is like a cross between phyllo and a\par
wonton wrapper. I would wrap these ingredients in this dough and then saut\'e9\par
them in clarified butter and slice them like a spring roll. Alongside I served\par
green tea ice cream. This covered a lot of bases for me: the warm and cold\par
temperatures, the Asian influence, and doing something with boring old rice\par
pudding.\par
The coolest compliment I ever got was from Andrew Carmellini [chef of New\par
York\rquote s A Voce] who was sitting down with us and asked about my background.\par
When I said I used to be a line cook, he said, \ldblquote I knew it \f2\emdash\f1  a pastry chef would\par
never come up with that!\rdblquote  It was the combination of techniques and flavors as\par
