We participate in an event called \ldblquote Plate and Pitchfork\rdblquote  that is held on a farm\par
with the food from the farm. The guests sit in the field among the corn and\par
tomatoes, and we cook a meal for them on a couple of grills. I made a corn soup\par
for this event. We removed the husks, then cut the kernels off the cob. Then we\par
used the husks, which produce a juice, to make a stock for the soup. If you were\par
to use cobs, you wouldn\rquote t get the same flavor. It is important to keep the corn\par
flavor pure. Most cooks would throw in a bunch of vegetables in the stock, and\par
what you\rquote d get then is a vegetable stock with corn. I want to have a corny flavor\par
in the end. We made a stock using the corn husks cooked with a little onion,\par
water, and salt, and let it cook for about 45 minutes. What came out was the\par
most amazing sweet broth. We added the corn, pureed it, and served it chilled. It\par
was so sweet and full of corn flavor you would have sworn there were cream and\par
sugar in it.\par
We now make a corn husk broth to add to a corn, chanterelle, and Dungeness\par
crab risotto with a touch of pesto. Basil pesto and corn really speaks to me. It is a\par
wonderful combination.\par
