Serve Dessert\par
The older I get, the more I like my dessert at 3:00 in the afternoon. I like it all by\par
itself, it has no competition and you are usually hungry. Your taste buds are wide\par
awake and you can appreciate what it is. Of course if we have people over for\par
dinner I can\rquote t get away with not serving dessert!\par
When you serve a dessert after a meal you are already full, not in a bad way,\par
but if you had a first course and main course your palate has gone through many\par
flavor components. At home I always take a little break and give people a\par
breather between dinner and dessert. I\rquote ll have my guests help with the dishes or,\par
if it\rquote s a formal party, I\rquote ll let them talk for a half hour and finish off the red wine.\par
It is not just for their stomachs but for the palate as well.\par
I hate when it comes to slicing a dessert and someone says, \ldblquote No, no, that is\par
too big!\rdblquote  I used to fight it and take it personally, so now I just ask in advance.\par
The guest appreciates it, has a small piece, and then has seconds. It is\par
recognizing that everyone has their own choice regarding how much they want\par
to eat. If I am serving a shortcake, I will put the fruit with a little cream on the\par
cake, then pass a bowl of whipped cream, so whether they want to pile it or keep\par
it light, they can.\par
