\f2\emdash\f1  GABRIEL KREUTHER, THE MODERN (NEW YORK CITY)\par
Fennel is a flavor I like so much that I have to show restraint with it. You can\par
add anything to it because other flavors really adhere to it. You can braise it in\par
olive oil and veal stock to get one flavor. Or you can braise it in olive oil, white\par
wine, and water and get a whole other flavor. Or you can quarter it, caramelize\par
it, and roast it in the oven \f2\emdash\f1  now you have a sugar flavor and it can become a\par
dessert. I love fennel every way including braised, caramelized, dried, candied,\par
and pureed. In the fall, I served raw shaved fennel with arugula, and shaved\par
Honeycrisp apple with a dressing made of apple cider, honey, and mustard.\par
Fennel puts the salad over the top with its crunch. In summer, we serve a fennel\par
and fig tarte tatin with duck. You get a Fig Newton flavor from the fig and\par
Pernod flavor from the fennel; they match really well.\par
