Fennel pollen has a light, fennel-anise flavor with a floral component. It is\par
delicate, so you don\rquote t cook with it \f2\emdash\f1  you just finish a dish with it. It is great on\par
lighter things like salads, poached or steamed flaky white fish, poultry, or pork.\par
When a dish has fennel pollen, even before the food hits your mouth you will\par
notice a floral smell that gets you thinking of summer, lighter foods, and\par
freshness. I use it with my sea trout dish, which is served with a simple salad of\par
green apple, fennel, jicama, pistachios, and dried gooseberries. The dish is\par
topped with the pollen blended with some yogurt, lemon juice, and preserved\par
lemon, which we drape over the fish. This dish just screams \ldblquote summer.\rdblquote  With a\par
glass of Sauvignon Blanc on the terrace in the early evening, you\rquote re set!\par
