Halibut from the East Coast is the most delicate and silky fish. It is different\par
than Alaskan halibut, which is drier, meatier, and more robust. East Coast halibut\par
is so delicate that anything can kill it. That is why we steam and poach so much\par
here: Even searing it too strongly in the pan will hurt a piece of halibut.\par
We\rquote ll poach halibut, then serve it with a blood orange vinaigrette made with\par
extra-virgin olive oil, which gives it a round and full flavor. The fish is then\par
served atop a carpaccio of golden beets that have been cooked in sherry vinegar.\par
The beets have a sweet-and-sour flavor to them. They are also very crunchy,\par
which I like with the creamy texture of the halibut. The vinaigrette brings the\par
right degree of acidity to the dish to make it exciting.\par
