HERBS (See specific herbs)\par
Herbs 101 with Jerry Traunfeld of The Herbfarm, Woodinville,\par
Washington\par
Working with herbs is very different from working with spices. With herbs, you\par
can really only work with a few at a time. With spices, you can throw so many\par
more together. An Indian dish may have more than a dozen spices in it. Here are\par
some guidelines: \f2\bullet\f1  Know your herb. Herbs range in intensity, so you need to\par
know the profile of the herb you are choosing at the start. You need to be careful;\par
for example, if you add rosemary to chervil it will overpower the chervil.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  You want to pair delicate with delicate or strong with strong. Chervil is\par
possibly the most delicate herb. Lemon basil and lemon thyme would be in the\par
middle. Lemon verbena or tarragon I would consider loud. Then you have bay\par
leaf which is light, until you add twenty together and it becomes strong.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Not all herbs are created equal, and they can vary within their categories or\par
season. Oregano can be mild, or hot and spicy. With mint, applemint is mild\par
while peppermint is strong. The season also has an effect on rosemary: in the\par
winter, rosemary is mild and in the summer, it is strong.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Herbs have regional affinities. Mediterranean herbs marry well together.\par
Rosemary and marjoram or thyme and savory are naturals together. Among\par
Asian herbs, lemongrass goes with mint and cilantro or mint and chives. In\par
France, you have lots of combinations: chervil, tarragon, chives, and parsley.\par
The one exception to France\rquote s herbs is tarragon, which is probably best on its\par
own.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Herbs also have seasonal affinities. Summer vegetables work with summer\par
herbs, as do winter vegetables with winter herbs. In summer, it is basil or\par
marjoram with tomatoes. Basil with zucchini is one of my favorite combinations.\par
In winter, sage and rosemary work with potatoes and root vegetables. Also in\par
winter, one of my favorite combinations is butternut squash with bay leaf and\par
nutmeg. Pumpkin and bay leaf together make the pumpkin taste even more\par
pumpkin-like.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  How to use the chosen herb. Soft-leaved herbs \f2\emdash\f1  such as basil, chervil, chives,\par
cilantro, dill, lovage, and sorrel \f2\emdash\f1  shouldn\rquote t be cooked because they will lose\par
their flavor. Tough-leaved herbs \f2\emdash\f1  such as bay leaf, savory, and rosemary \f2\emdash\f1\par
can go into dishes and stand up to heat and cooking.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Choose an herb that is the same intensity as your protein. Halibut is a gentletasting fish, which leads to gentle herbs like cilantro, chives, or chervil. Smelt is\par
a local fish that is oily, so here we look to stronger herbs like oregano, savory, or\par
rosemary.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Herbs aren\rquote t exclusive to savory dishes. Anise hyssop works with most stone\par
fruits like peaches. Cinnamon basil works with blue huckleberries. Cinnamon\par
with blueberries really intensifies the flavor of the blueberry. Lavender works\par
with plums or peaches. Lemony herbs like basil or anise hyssop work with\par
watermelon. Rosemary works with apples or pears. Sage works with tart\par
cherries. Tarragon works with muskmelon.\par
We grow forty different tomatoes and eight different basils. Our farmer planted\par
the tomatoes surrounded by the basil, and I thought he did it because they taste\par
good together. It turns out that doing so attracts beneficial insects to each. Our\par
farmer believes that tomato and basil work so well on the plate because they\par
work so well in the field. He also explained that if you plant certain basils next\par
to tomatoes, you can taste it in the tomato.\par
All our cooks take care of their own section of the herb garden. The gardemanger cooks [who prepare appetizers] look after the chives and chervil. The\par
fish cooks care for the lemon herbs like lemon thyme and lemongrass, and the\par
meat cooks for the rosemary, sage, and thyme. Our pastry cooks tend the edible\par
flowers that can be candied, and mint and lemon verbena, which they use in\par
sorbets.\par
