I work with a local lamb farmer in the Willamette Valley who has true spring\par
lamb in the spring. We have a spit and every Friday night we roast a whole lamb.\par
I am a big fan of lamb shoulder. It can take a beating and in the end come out\par
glorious tasting! There is an old French technique where they cook ham in hay.\par
The hay is submerged in water; then they put the ham on it to cook. It is\par
amazing. We adapted this technique to the lamb. We had our farmer collect the\par
hay and grass in the field where the lamb grazed with the thinking that this is\par
what the lamb actually ate. We then dry the hay by letting it sit out overnight on\par
a tray, so it becomes really butterscotchy and barnyardy. You can use any hay for\par
this technique but I\rquote m just a purist.\par
We brine a boneless shoulder of lamb for 24 hours in a brining solution of 1\par
cup of salt and 1\f2\u8260?\f1 4 cup of sugar in a gallon of water, [adding] some peppercorns,\par
bay leaf, a couple of cardamom pods, a cinnamon stick, and cumin. The brine is\par
brought to a boil, cooled down, and the lamb goes in. After the brining we rub\par
the lamb with garlic and summer savory and tie it up into a log and put it on the\par
bed of hay, drizzle it with white wine, cover it, and put it in the oven. It is nature\par
going back on itself. The lamb ate the hay, the hay makes the lamb taste better.\par
When it\rquote s cooked, the flavors are intense but pleasant and it becomes something\par
else. When lavender is in season, I\rquote ll throw some in the hay as well and it is\par
delicious.\par
With the lamb I like to serve a stuffed tomato Proven\'e7al [typically a\par
combination of basil, bread crumbs, garlic, olive oil]. You want to serve\par
