Tips: Strive for balance over an entire menu, i.e., appetizer, entr\'e9e, and\par
dessert. Envision the course of a menu as a piece of music having a melody,\par
rhythm, and tempo.\par
When planning a menu, pick the dessert or the entr\'e9e first and have the other\par
one match it, in terms of style and preparation. If you are doing an entr\'e9e that\par
requires last-minute time in the kitchen, don\rquote t serve a dessert that requires lastminute time as well. If you have a main course that takes last-minute work, serve\par
a dessert that can be made a day ahead \f2\emdash\f1  or if your dessert is what needs lastminute attention, serve it after a stew or lasagna. When deciding what to make,\par
remember: The heavier the main course, the lighter the dessert should be, or vice\par
versa. I was recently going through some of my earlier books and was shocked\par
when I looked at the recipes. One recipe for a chocolate cake that we served at\par
Stars was served in big wedges. I was amazed we used to serve such a huge\par
portion! People can\rquote t eat like that anymore. At the same time, the cake is so good\par
I still want to serve it so I work backward. I will serve a chicken or something\par
else light for the main course, not a prime rib of beef.\par
