Mushrooms Year-Round\par
Spring. This is the start of the morel season. One of the reasons I came to work\par
in Oregon was one day I was working in a kitchen in France and a box of morels\par
arrived with a tag on it that said \ldblquote Oregon.\rdblquote\par
Summer. The morels dwindle away, and we get a brief stint of porcini/cepes.\par
Late summer is golden and white chanterelle season.\par
Fall. The porcini come back and we also get in matsutake mushrooms as well.\par
We have [Pacific Northwest] black and white truffles here and the season starts\par
in November. They are pretty flavorful but it is important to realize they are\par
different from European truffles \f2\emdash\f1  not to mention a lot less expensive.\par
I\rquote m not a big fan of cultivated mushrooms but I do like a few. King oyster or\par
trumpet royal are the same mushroom and it is one of my favorites. Portobellos\par
are also good, though they are a little \lquote 70s.\par
I am suspicious of some dried mushrooms you find in the supermarket only\par
because you don\rquote t know how old they are and how much flavor they will have.\par
Buying and Cleaning Mushrooms\par
When it comes to mushrooms, every kind needs to be well cleaned because there\par
is nothing worse than getting a mouthful of grit. I wash them all by soaking them\par
in a bowl of water and pulling them out. The key to remember is that you want\par
to use mushrooms soon after washing them. Don\rquote t wash them a day ahead.\par
For morel mushrooms, you need to know how to cook them, and slicing them\par
up fresh and throwing them in a pan is not it. It is very important to clean them\par
and I recommend blanching them. Fill a pot with cold water, toss in a handful of\par
salt and then the mushrooms. Bring the pot to a boil, scoop out the mushrooms,\par
spread them out, and lightly squeeze them dry. As you dry them, take a good\par
look at them to make sure they are free of twigs and such.\par
Seasoning Mushrooms\par
When it comes to seasoning mushrooms, savory works across the board. The\par
seasoning combination that I\rquote ve used in my kitchen from day one is a raw\par
parsley and garlic combination that in French is called persillade. After the\par
mushrooms have been saut\'e9ed in butter or olive oil, at the last second you toss in\par
this combination with a pinch of salt. That is all a mushroom needs most of the\par
time!\par
If you are roasting porcini or king oyster mushrooms, roast them on a bed of\par
savory or thyme for extra flavor.\par
