Good cooking transcends all cultures. You can take inspiration from all around\par
the world and apply it to what you are cooking without making it \ldblquote fusion.\rdblquote  In\par
some cases, you can even take a classic and make it taste better. I worked with\par
Floyd Cardoz [chef of the Indian restaurant Tabla in New York City] and learned\par
a lot about Indian spicing and technique from him. One technique was turka,\par
which is where you fry spices in oil or ghee [Indian clarified butter] until they\par
pop. It really opens up the flavor of the spices.\par
I use this cross-cultural technique when making a veal dish with a great\par
mustard sauce, which is a classic French dish, and the result is not a fusion dish:\par
Take black, yellow, and red mustard seeds and toast them in butter or olive oil\par
until they pop; then add some shallots and vermouth and reduce it. Then, add\par
veal stock with a splash of cream and Dijon mustard. The result is a very\par
complex sauce with a much deeper flavor, versus simply combining some cream\par
and mustard together in the pan.\par
