\f2\emdash\f1  ALEXANDRA RAIJ, T\'cdA POL (NEW YORK CITY) People do not\par
understand parsley; they think it is green specks. But it is wonderful with fish. If\par
you make a straight-up linguini with clam sauce, you want a big handful of\par
chopped parsley in there \f2\emdash\f1  not for the appearance, but for the taste. It is an\par
important component in a lot of dishes and needs to be there. It can also be used\par
as a sauce all on its own. If you sprinkle it on a steak, it will not have the impact\par
that it would on fish. On the other hand, if you make a Ma\'eetre d\rquote h\'f4tel butter\par
[butter flavored with lemon juice and parsley] and put it on the steak, the parsley\par
has a role there. On vegetables, if you make glazed carrots or pearl onions or a\par
stew with lots of vegetables, parsley stirred in at the last moment is good stuff.\par
As for my choice of parsley, I always use flat Italian-style parsley.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  DAVID WALTUCK, CHANTERELLE (NEW YORK CITY) Salsa verde is\par
my favorite all-purpose condiment at home. I like it on fish, lamb, and steak. It is\par
made with anchovy, garlic, shallots, olive oil, and herbs \f2\emdash\f1  primarily parsley,\par
but also chervil, chives, tarragon, a little bit of marjoram, and sometimes a little\par
mint if I am in the mood. I add the acid at the last moment so it won\rquote t change the\par
color of the herbs, and will choose between Banyuls or red wine vinegar, or\par
lemon juice. If I am serving meat, I will use vinegar; if I am serving fish, I will\par
use lemon. Even though it changes color once the acid is added, it lasts a few\par
days. It is really good on a piece of bread or with some fresh farmer\rquote s cheese as\par
