Pairing Pastas with Sauces\par
Which sauces pair best with which pastas? We asked chef Odette Fada of New\par
York City\rquote s San Domenico restaurant.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Angel hair: In Italy, angel hair pasta is served to old people who can\rquote t chew.\par
It\rquote s for grandparents, or for others to eat when they are sick. The problem with\par
angel hair pasta is it\rquote s so thin it\rquote s hard to cook al dente, and I like my pasta a\par
little chewy.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Bow tie: Fresh bow tie is great when made by hand, because it stays folded and\par
doesn\rquote t open into a square. I like to serve it with vegetables and tomato-based\par
sauces.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Fettuccine: This is a flavorful pasta and is good with a Bolognese sauce.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Fusilli: I like their [corkscrew] shape, but they tend to break easily so they are\par
not that attractive when you cook them in a restaurant setting. I like them at\par
home in a salad or with some pesto because the pesto sticks to it.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Hollow pasta [e.g., macaroni, penne, rigatoni]: Good with sauces that have big\par
chunks in them so that the sauce pieces go inside whole. I like to do penne with\par
fresh peas because the peas will slip inside, so you\rquote ll sometimes get a little\par
surprise when you\rquote re chewing.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Pappardelle: This is a strong, rustic pasta. I like it with rabbit sauce, a rago\'fbt,\par
or a fish sauce that has some character.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Small pasta [e.g., rice-, shell-, or star-shaped]: These are good for soups and\par
brothy dishes. For example, you would use them with a brothy fish dish.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Spaghetti: Everything goes with spaghetti! It is a pasta that sauce sticks to.\par
Everything from tomato sauce to pesto to pecorino with black pepper is great\par
with spaghetti.\par
Or, if you\rquote re starting with the sauce:\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Carbonara: Spaghetti or bucatini, you want a pasta that the sauce will stick to.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Cream: Fettuccine, pappardelle, or gnocchi, since cream is so rich you want a\par
strong-flavored pasta or, in the last case, gnocchi \f2\emdash\f1  one that is made with some\par
egg in it.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Game: Pappardelle or fettuccine; you want an egg-rich pasta with some flavor.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Olive oil and garlic: Spaghetti.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Pesto: Fusilli.\par
\f2\bullet\f1  Tomato: This works with almost all pasta shapes, from small to large.\par
I have played with lots of flavored pasta doughs. One of my favorites is olive\par
because it holds its flavor. Other flavors that hold up well are squid ink and\par
saffron. I have also made a pappardelle with cocoa powder that I paired with\par
game sauce that worked great. If you wanted to achieve a particular color, you\par
could create red pasta with beets, green pasta with spinach, and black pasta with\par
squid ink.\par
