Chef Odette Fada of New York\rquote s San Domenico on Making\par
Ravioli\par
I love ravioli! Anything and everything goes in my ravioli \f2\emdash\f1  I have used\par
everything from chestnuts to cheese to fish, meat, and vegetables. You can vary\par
the ravioli dough as well as the stuffing. For example, I serve ravioli stuffed with\par
sea urchin and the dough is light and made with just flour and water. For a\par
stronger filling like lamb, I will use some egg in the dough which makes it\par
bigger flavored. One of my favorite ravioli stuffings is black truffle and pancetta.\par
The truffle provides a crunchiness when you bite into it.\par
One of the greatest ravioli we do dates back to the chef for the last king of\par
Italy at the beginning of the twentieth century. It is stuffed with spinach, truffle,\par
Parmesan cheese, and an egg yolk, and served with butter, truffle, and Parmesan\par
cheese. When the ravioli is cooked, it is served with the yolk warm but not\par
cooked. It is truly an amazing dish.\par
In Italy during the winter, you would typically have some slices of sausage on\par
top of a plate of lentils. I decided to combine the two into a ravioli dish. Now,\par
one of my other favorite dishes is our ravioli stuffed with cotechino [sausage]\par
and lentils. The lentils are cooked with rosemary, garlic, extra-virgin olive oil,\par
and prosciutto skin, and go into the ravioli with the sausage, parsley, and\par
Parmesan cheese. The dish is finished with some strong extra-virgin olive oil,\par
parsley, and a crack of pepper.\par
