Odette Fada of New York\rquote s San Domenico on Risotto\par
I am from Northern Italy and grew up eating risotto. Back then, we mainly ate\par
risotto Milanese [i.e., saffron risotto, traditionally served with osso buco or with\par
a mild pork sausage crumbled in with some rosemary]. We would also put it in\par
soup \f2\emdash\f1  or even just eat it simply with some grated cheese.\par
I love it because it only takes one pan, and it is ready in 20 minutes! People\par
think it takes a long time but if you were to cook a piece of fish, wash greens,\par
and make a salad dressing, that would take just as long.\par
You can make risotto with almost anything. I love it with fruit, vegetables, or\par
fish. One of my favorite fruit risottos is a seasonal one with pears and\par
Gorgonzola. The pears give a nice, sweet crunch to the dish. I also like making\par
risotto with Prosecco, strawberries, and nettles.\par
A classic combination in Italy in fall is game with blueberry jam and\par
mushrooms. I have adapted this and for over twenty years have been serving\par
risotto with porcini mushrooms and blueberries tossed in at the last second.\par
I also like to make a risotto with fresh herbs like rosemary, thyme, or oregano\par
\f2\emdash\f1  and then at the end I\rquote ll cover it with an extra-thin slice of lard [pork jowl] that\par
has a mild flavor. It just melts into the risotto and is out of this world.\par
Each ingredient you add to your risotto will dictate when it should be added. If it\par
is something delicate like a berry, it gets added very late so it will not break up.\par
If you are making a seafood risotto \f2\emdash\f1  say, with octopus \f2\emdash\f1  it should be added\par
early so it has time to cook all the way through.\par
