Vitaly Paley of Portland\rquote s Paley\rquote s Place on Cooking Salmon on a\par
Plank\par
Salmon is a big part of cooking in the Northwest. We get ours anywhere from\par
Oregon up to Alaska.\par
The first cooking process that comes to mind in this part of the country is\par
called cedar planking, which is a Native American technique. You see planking\par
in all the best cooking catalogs, but the problem is that you cook the fish, throw\par
it out, and keep the plank because the plank is inevitably more expensive than\par
the fish! So here is one tip: Instead, do what we do and go to a lumber yard and\par
pick up untreated cedar shingles. They come in a huge bundle for $16.\par
To get the most out of plank cooking, the salmon needs to be brined or\par
marinated. I have two favorite marinades \f2\emdash\f1  one that is wet, and one that is dry.\par
The wet marinade is a 60/40 mixture of soy sauce and cream sherry, lots of\par
sliced ginger, heads of garlic cut in half, and chopped scallions. The sherry adds\par
just a touch of sweetness to the fish, which I like. Let the fish sit in that marinade\par
for a couple of hours and then it is ready to take on the smoke.\par
The dry marinade is a more traditional marinade of a 60/40 ratio of brown\par
sugar and salt with orange zest [grated] on a microplane [fine grater]. I mix this\par
all together and lavishly rub it over a salmon with the skin on, which protects it\par
from getting too salty or sweet. The sugar in this rub balances out the salt and\par
adds another dimension to the fish with caramelization happening a lot quicker.\par
The sweetness is almost hidden; it is that \ldblquote What\rquote s-that-flavor?\rdblquote  aspect to the\par
fish. Marinate for a couple of hours, then wipe off the rub slightly, and it is ready\par
to go. The 60/40 ratio of sugar to salt is good because it is pretty forgiving if you\par
leave the fish in the marinade a half hour too long.\par
I recommend brushing the plank lightly with some olive oil, throwing it on a\par
hot grill, putting the fish on, and letting it catch on fire, because when the plank\par
is on fire, that is the flavor you are looking for. When the burning plank gets\par
close to the fish, cover the grill to smother the fire and let the smoke do the rest\par
of the work.\par
Salmon has been my favorite fish since I learned to cook it correctly. It is so\par
versatile: you can smoke it, marinate it, or even serve it raw. Because it is rich\par
and fatty, it pairs well with everything from a red wine sauce to a simple\par
vinaigrette.\par
