\f2\emdash\f1  BRADFORD THOMPSON, MARY ELAINE\rquote S AT THE PHOENICIAN (SCOTTSDALE,\par
ARIZONA)\par
There is salt in almost all of my desserts. However, you would not know it was\par
there until I took it out \f2\emdash\f1  which is how it should be. You don\rquote t need to taste the\par
salt, but it helps open the palate and stimulates your taste buds. With something\par
fatty like chocolate, you need some salt to brighten it up. I use all sorts of salts\par
with my desserts. We are making a peanut butter and jelly bonbon that I pair\par
with smoked Brittany sea salt. Maldon salt is shaved and more about texture,\par
because it is not as strong; I would use it on a pancake or something creamy.\par
Fleur de sel is a salt with texture and ocean floral notes, and would go well on\par
our panini which have cheese, arugula, and vinaigrette.\par
\f2\emdash\f1  JOHNNY IUZZINI, JEAN GEORGES (NEW YORK CITY)\par
Salt goes into almost every dough we make and is something that makes flavors\par
pop. Some chefs can go a little overboard, but desserts should still be sweet. Salt\par
works well with caramel and chocolate, obviously. I also use a vanilla salt with\par
a classic sweet potato tart that is cut into four slices with a few grains on each\par
slice. The salt reinforces the savoriness of the sweet potato and plays off the\par
brightness of the preserved lemon on the plate.\par
